<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The Communication performance. Your work goes public.</p>
  <p>This is the unit's Communication performance, and it is the upgrade over a peer-only panel. You present your neighbourhood redesign as a real public activity at the school's environmental showcase, framed for a real municipal audience: the Greater Chennai Corporation, the CMDA, or your ward office. Your live activity teaches visitors the choice your neighbourhood faces, and your shareable artifact carries the same message to people who never stopped by, with consent in place. This is the fifth defense of the year, and the first one delivered to strangers rather than a panel of classmates.</p>
  <p>The bar is not a polished slogan. Plenty of people can make a neighbourhood sound wonderful. The bar is whether your audience walks away able to see <strong>both</strong> what your plan achieves <strong>and</strong> what it costs. A visitor who only heard the good news did not get the real lesson, which is that liveable places are made by choosing, not by wishing. The strongest stations make the visitor do the choosing for a moment, and feel the trade-off from the inside.</p>
  <p>Format and care. If a live station is not right for you, a <strong>pre-recorded video</strong> activity is available with prior approval. Anyone who appears in a public piece has given <strong>consent</strong>, with an opt-out, and there is always a <strong>non-public fallback</strong>: you can present and be assessed without anything being posted anywhere. (Whether the unit runs during the school's showcase week is still being scheduled, so nothing here is tied to a date.)</p>
</section>

